n style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> involve the child being removed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">family and being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">placed into a residential care setting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sometimes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a lo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng way from home.  Frequently a residential option is undertaken because alternative measures such as foster care, have broken down re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">peatedly.  Sometimes residential care is imposed by a Court seeking to remove the child or young person from its immediate surroundings.  At Mayfield we have experienced a wide range of reasons for placements.  Some children and young people come with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">full blessing of their parents or guardians and regard Mayfield as a place of safety where a young person can develop in a way they could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have done in their normal family location.  Some children come under Court Orders to remove them from their parent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s for reasons of neglect.  Whatever the reason the placement of a child or young person in a residential home is a very serious event in their lives.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children going into residential care do so at a very vulnerable time in their lives. What is essential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is to provide a stable caring environment. This needs for example continuity of staff. Children are unsettled if all they see are temporary or agency staff. They need to build up trust and need consistent boundaries.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Too often children’s homes are run thro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ugh employing the cheapest possible staffing.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have a structured approach to placing children into residential care. At Mayfield we have tendered with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and sit on their approved placement lists. Whenever a child need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s to go into care we are contacted and submit a proposal based on the needs of the child. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> seem to work on an emergency basis with individual social workers trying desperately to find a bed for a child. They have no list of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> approved homes rather they either go to the same providers irrespective of quality or they ring round any home they can find. That is not to put any blame on the social workers or the children’s departments. They work under intense pressure and often a ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ild going into</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> residential care is a last resort. It is the plac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ement system that is at fault.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The costs of placing a child into residential care are high. From £2,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">00 per week if a child has a full time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Substantially more in certain circumstance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s depending on the individual needs of the child. It is a great expense at times of financial strain for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Many children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> never come out of care.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">THE CORPORATE MODEL OF </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CHILDREN’S HOMES</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children’s homes are not all bad.  In many circumstances a child can thrive and develop further through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> time in a children’s home.  We consider Mayfield to be an excellent experience where children and young people can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reach out and experience as ful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l a life as their condition allows</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  However, this is not a matter of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chance;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it is because Mayfield has the facilities, a dedicated workforce, a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">skilful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">management team and most of all owners who are willing to invest in order to meet the high standards.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We regard investment in the future as far more important than short term profit. Too many providers take the opposite view. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are many types of proprietors of children’s homes.  Some still remain under </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthority control although these are conti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nuing to decline.  The problem with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthority homes is that they often suffer from a lack of investment and it is an extremely costly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> option</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthority to maintain the full expense of running the home whether it is full or not.  The gene</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ral view of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is that such child care should be outsourced to private providers.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in general prefer to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> spot purchas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> residential placements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rather than maintaining </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their own children’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> homes. That way they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">only have to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> buy the exact number of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s required.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst there are many children’s homes run as charities, the bulk of the provision is provided by privately owned homes which are effectively competing against each other for new placements from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The privately owned children’s home sector is extremely fragmented with the majority of homes owned by individuals.  Many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">entrepreneurs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> persuaded to go into the children’s home sector by the high level of fees that are paid ranging from £2,500 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">per week</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through to in excess of £4,000 per week with more in extreme cases.   Many of these homes are set up in places were residential accommodation is less expensive such that placements are often a l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ong way from the child’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> home.  In some circumstances it may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be a great advantage for the child to be located at a distance from home, for example where matters of protection are involved.  However, in m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cases it is extremely inconvenient and indeed unfortunate that children are placed so far from their original home.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no doubt that the running of children’s home is an extremely expensive and complex operation.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The regulations involved are very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thorough and rightly so. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This has deterred the setting up of new homes in areas where there is most need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for example in London. New homes have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sprung up in areas where housing is cheap. Often this has been through the conversion of small 3 or 4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> bedroom houses which arguably do not have the range of facilities best suited for children.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The map of children’s homes in England does not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overlap </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the same population map.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In many cases, children’s homes are no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> maintained to a sufficiently high </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enough </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">standard.  Often this is the case where the owners wish to maximise profits and therefore repairs and renewals of the fabric and premises are not as high a priority as they should be.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There needs to be a fundamental overha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l of what is suitable accommodati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on for children’s homes. On a national level there needs to be a far greater cohesive policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rather than allowing the free market to prevail with individual social workers placing children on a spot purchasing basis with homes in unsuitable places or whic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h do not for example have proper staff training or do not maintain buildings to a high enough standard.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">FUNDAMENTAL PROBLEMS IN THE RESIDENTIAL SECTOR</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The fundamental problem is the spot purchasing of places by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  This makes it very difficult for the owners of children’s homes to plan ahead with any certainty.  There should be a far greater partnership working between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the children’s home sector to provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) greater </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">certainty of income for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the owners of the homes and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(ii) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies greater </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">control over costs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">whilst </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">maint</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the highest possible standards.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst it is difficult for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to predict when placements will be required, nevertheless a more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">planned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">system would be better for all concerned.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is staggering to learn how many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> place children in homes which are only rated adequate by Ofsted. It is a scandal that first such homes are allowed to continue and second </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are not working with homes such as Mayfield to start new homes nearer to where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> authority demand is greatest.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">TRANSPARENCY</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst transparency is of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> course important in the monitoring of any part of public expenditure it is not by itself going to i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mprove the lives of children in care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Clearly there is a frustration in being aware of inadequacies within the residential care system but not being able to easily identify the poor performers. However “naming and shaming” is not an appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">measure in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">these circumstances.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The location of children’s homes is not a matter for public knowledge.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Simply publicising poorly performing homes does not solve the problem or improve the lives of children in their care.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The transparency has to come from revealing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are continuing to use homes that only reach an adequate measure of performance. I am not aware of how Ofsted work with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Ofsted inspect all children’s homes. When they come across a poorly run home how pro-active a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re they in contacting every </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who use that home</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HIGHER QUALITY</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Of course the answer to improving the care of children in a residential setting is to improve standards and improve quality. But announcing this as an objective is meaningless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unless steps are taken to change the system. The better run homes need to be encouraged to expand and open new homes in geographical areas where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is an unfulfilled need. This can only be achieved by a more structured approach to placement. The spot pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rchasing system by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> individual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> encourages a fragmented approach.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Often placements have to be done quickly. Dealing with vulnerable children is by definition unpredictable. Some placements can be done in a measured basis over time. Others a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re emergency. In the latter cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> speed of placement takes priority over quality. A better system would be for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to block purchase bed spaces with quality providers, only paying the full cost if all beds are used but giving the home owner </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some certainty of income and enabling the better providers to invest in new homes.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Higher quality is an ethos that many homes do not aspire to. Maximising profits in the short term cannot always be aligned with a long term drive to quality. Quality com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es about through investment in people and buildings. It reflects the passion of managers and owners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be the best”.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">TOUGHER INSPECTIONS</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We would welcome the use of tougher inspections to improve overall standards as long as an effective system is put in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> place to put an end to poor quality homes and to encourage better operators to expand.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The annual Ofsted inspection is a tough test. Why are there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inspections from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to ensure that their money is being well spent? Do Ofsted and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">loc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not need to join forces in ensuring that children are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not left in poorly run homes?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="fo